ed the banished, many of those same people also turned against their comrades. Wang describes the ways in which the state sought to remold the intellectuals, and he illuminates the strategies the exiles used to deal with camp officials and improve their chances of survival.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aExileszChinazManchuriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aForced laborzChinazManchuriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aIntellectualszChinazBeijingxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor campszChinazManchuriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical persecutionzChinazBeijingxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies. 4aCriminology. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501714016zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501714016423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501714016/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles